notesStmt.note: This manuscript, completed in the later part of the thirteenth century, contains William of Tyre's Estoire d'Eracles (to 1229), Les Faits des Romains (continuation, Tiberius to Julian), and a letter of Prester John. While the origin of the manuscript is debatable between Acre and Paris, Jaroslav Folda suggests a strong connection with Epinal 45, a manuscript known to have been created in Paris during this same time. Versions of William of Tyre's work were particularly popular in France during the latter part of the thirteenth century. The volume of William de Tyre's history of the Crusades housed at the Walters Art Museum features eighteen historiated initials, completed by four different artists' hands, of varying competence. What sets this particular manuscript apart from its contemporaries is the two unusual appended texts and its selective pictorial style.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is French, Old (842-ca.1400).

msItem.note: History includes the text for 1095-1184, with continuation through 1229; text divided by sixteen historiated initials and fourteen large flourished initials

msItem.title: Les Faits des Romains
msItem.incipit: Nous vous avons dit devant que li empereur tyberius
msItem.note: Text divided into sixty-five chapters; rubrics left blank; continuation of history of Roman emperors, from Tiberius through Julian, with many references to Seneca

msItem.title: Letter of Prester John
msItem.incipit: Prestre Iehans par la graice de ihesucrist

support.p: Medium- to heavy-weight parchment; unevenly and at times poorly finished, with color and texture ranging widely; many mended and unmended holes, some large and within textblock (e.g. see fol. 189); many missing corners; candle wax spilled on pages throughout

supportDesc.foliation: Original foliation in red Roman numerals, upper left corners, versos; nineteenth-century pencil foliation on upper right corners, rectos, now almost completely erased; modern pencil foliation, upper right corners, rectos (used here)

p.formula: Quires 1-6: 12 (fols. 1-72); Quire 7: 8 (fols. 73-80); Quires 8-13: 12 (fols. 81-152); Quire 14: 8 (fols. 153-160); Quires 15-30: 12 (fols. 161-352); Quire 31: 4 (fols. 353-356); Quire 32: 6, composed of six singletons stitched together (fols. 357-362)
p.signatures: Signatures rarely visible, give upper-case letter and roman numeral (e.g. fols. 153-157, where "NI"-"NV" is visible in lead); quire numbers at times visible in form of dark brown ink Roman numerals, middle of lower margins, last versos; modern pencil quire numbers in Arabic numerals lower left corners first rectos
p.catchwords: Occasionally visible lower right of last verso in quire

layoutDesc.layout: Ruled in lead except for fols. 269-328, which are ruled in brown crayon

handDesc.handNote: Written in irregular textura by several hands: hand changes notable at fols. 142, 151, 269, and 329

decoDesc.decoNote: Historiated initials fols. 1r, 15r, 29r, 33r, 62r, 137r, 145r, 157v, 171v, 180v, 203v, 222r, 229v, 235r, 252r, and 265v; large flourished initials fols. 24r, 42r, 52r, 72v, 82v, 121v, 133v, 144v, 171r, 222v, 237v, 251v, 260r, and 300r

Eighteen historiated initials (6-13 lines), found at the beginnings of seven books, nine chapters, as well as at beginning of other two appended texts; fourteen large flourished initials filled with intricate penwork at some major chapter divisions (7-9 lines); smaller flourished initials at beginnings of three books, and at beginnings of secondary text divisions throughout (3 lines); rubrics in red; text in dark brown ink; four different artists' hands identifiable: Hand A: fols. 1r and 357r; Hand B: fols. 15r, 29r, 137r, 157v, 229v, and 235r; Hand C: fols. 33r, 145r, 171v, 203v (or possibly Hand B), 329r; Hand D: fols. 62r, 180v, 222r, and 252r

decoNote.title: Initial "L" with (above) the Crucifixion, and the First Crusade being preached by Pope Urban II; (below) man kneeling in prayer before altar, and people worshiping idols
Initial "V" with Godefroy de Bouillon leaving for Holy Land with knights
Initial "N" with battle between the forces of Qilij Arslan and the Crusaders in Asia Minor
Initial "O" with Tancred receiving gifts from Turkish and Armenian satraps
Initial "C" with the emperor of Constantinople receiving Crusader envoys
Initial "Q" with man handing knights in tent the key to the city of Tyre
Initial "R" with the coronation of King Fulk
Initial "A" with the Count of Edessa and the Prince of Antioch playing dice on a chess board while a knight sleeps

note.p: Note: this has usually been described as a scene of men playing chess, but close examination reveals dice on the board rather than chess pieces. This may be a strange conflation of two traditions associated with this story, in which they are usually described as playing dice, but are sometimes depicted playing chess.

decoNote.title: Initial "N" with two laymen crowning King Baldwin
Initial "P" with Bernard of Clairvaux preaching the Second Crusade
Initial "O" with Patriarch Amaury of Antioch opposing the marriage of Raynauld of Châtillon and Constance
Initial "E" with the funeral service of King Baldwin III
Initial "S" with Crusader envoys and two men discussing renewal of treaty between King of Jerusalem and Sultan of Egypt
Initial "A" with the siege of Alexandria
Initial "Q" with Patriarch Amaury of Constantinople crowning Baldwin IV
Initial "D" with Guy of Lusignan's marriage to Sibylle, sister of Baldwin IV
Initial "N" with the Pharisees and Sadducees debating
Initial "P" with Prester John handing a letter for the Pope to a messenger

binding.p: Binding by Léon Gruel, Paris, early twentieth century; red velvet, resewn on six tawed straps; in eighteenth or early nineteenth century, edges of pages speckled with orange and grey, and paper tabs added; leather tabs added late nineteenth or early twentieth century; Gruel's original telescopic book box, stamped in gold with his name, replaced by Walters conservation department in the second half of the twentieth century

history.provenance: Produced in northern France, possibly Paris, in the late thirteenth century; early ownership inscription erased, fol. 362r

Several later inscriptions survive on fol. 362v in various states of legibility; upper left: fifteenth-century inscription reads "Cest li Roman de Goudeffroy de bullion Explicit"; to right of this inscription (somewhat effaced) in a different hand "Cest ly Roman godefroy de bullon que...p[our] xlvii m auril"; below both is drawn rectangular box which originally contained inscription (now erased); in lower left corner is inscribed ".xxx. l[ivres]"
